    {
        "content": "<p>I had thought that <code>:=</code> in mathematics came from some Pascal influence, but it turns out to go back to 1894 for \"is equal by definition to\". <a href=\"https://www.math.ucdavis.edu/~anne/WQ2007/mat67-Common_Math_Symbols.pdf\">https://www.math.ucdavis.edu/~anne/WQ2007/mat67-Common_Math_Symbols.pdf</a></p>\n<p>If you call it \"assignment\", don't get the wrong idea that it's putting a value into a variable. In <code>let x := 2</code> for example, this <em>creates</em> a new definition <code>x</code> that is equal to <code>2</code> (\"let <code>x</code> be 2\" is how I'd read it in words). If you then do <code>let x := 4</code> later, the old definition is still there, but it's <em>shadowed</em>, meaning \"<code>x</code>\" refers to the new definition; there are tricks to refer to the old one.</p>\n<p>(However, if you use <code>do</code> notation, then <code>:=</code> can be used in a way that really could said to be an assignment.)</p>",
        "id": 444043487,
        "sender_full_name": "Kyle Miller",
        "timestamp": 1718122532
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>great replies - thanks!</p>\n<p>I've been reading <code>:=</code> in mathematics content as \"defined as\", where as <code>=</code> means are equivalent by virtue of some other reasoning</p>\n<p>I think \"defined as\" is probably a good way to read it in Lean code too. (noting the shadowing complexity you mentioned)</p>",
        "id": 444057574,
        "sender_full_name": "rzeta0",
        "timestamp": 1718126083
    },
